\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:related}

The landscape of prompt optimization encompasses diverse approaches that differ fundamentally in their theoretical assumptions, computational requirements, and practical constraints. We organize the 21 most relevant systems into five categories and evaluate each against the desiderata established in \S\ref{sec:introduction}. Table~\ref{tab:prior-art} provides a comprehensive comparison across eight dimensions.

\subsection{Compression-Based Methods}

Compression-based approaches reduce prompt length by identifying and removing tokens that contribute minimally to task performance, typically using information-theoretic criteria or learned compression models.

\textbf{LLMLingua} \cite{jiang2023llmlingua} introduced budget-constrained prompt compression using perplexity-based token importance scoring from a small auxiliary language model. The method achieves compression ratios of up to 20$\times$ while preserving downstream task performance. However, it requires inference through a secondary model, operates without tokenizer alignment awareness, and produces non-deterministic results due to its dependence on model perplexity estimates.

\textbf{LLMLingua-2} \cite{pan2024llmlingua2} reformulates prompt compression as a token classification problem, training a compact model to predict which tokens can be safely removed. This approach achieves faster compression than its predecessor and better preserves key information. Nevertheless, it requires a trained compression model, lacks causal attention grounding, and cannot guarantee deterministic outputs across different model versions.

\textbf{Selective Context} \cite{li2023compressing} computes self-information for each lexical unit and removes those below a threshold, achieving compression without task-specific training. While elegant in its simplicity, the method is agnostic to tokenizer boundaries and positional attention patterns.

\textbf{LongLLMLingua} \cite{jiang2024longllmlingua} extends the LLMLingua framework specifically for long-context scenarios, introducing question-aware compression that conditions token importance on the downstream query. This addresses a limitation of context-agnostic compression but retains the dependency on auxiliary model inference.

\textbf{Gist Tokens} \cite{mu2023learning} take a fundamentally different approach by training models to compress prompts into a small number of learned ``gist'' token embeddings that capture the semantic content of the original prompt. While this achieves extreme compression ratios, it requires model fine-tuning and is incompatible with black-box API access.

\textbf{AutoCompressors} \cite{chevalier2023adapting} similarly learn to compress long contexts into compact summary vectors through recursive summarization during pre-training. Like Gist Tokens, this approach modifies the model itself and is therefore incompatible with black-box deployment scenarios.

\textbf{LeanContext} \cite{arefeen2024leancontext} employs reinforcement learning to train a compression policy that selects which context elements to retain. The method achieves competitive compression ratios but introduces non-determinism through its learned policy and requires training infrastructure.

A common limitation across compression-based methods is their treatment of all token positions as equivalent---none accounts for the differential attention patterns across positions in causal transformers, and none aligns compression decisions with BPE tokenization boundaries.

\textbf{CompactPrompt} \cite{compactprompt2025} introduces an LLM-free heuristic approach using n-gram abbreviation and quantization, achieving up to 1.44$\times$ compression. As the only other rule-based system that avoids LLM dependency, CompactPrompt is the closest analogue to TSCG in the heuristic space. However, CompactPrompt operates at the \emph{lexical} level (abbreviating words and n-grams), while TSCG operates at the \emph{syntactic} level (restructuring grammar, reordering for causal attention, aligning with tokenizer boundaries). This fundamental difference explains the compression gap: CompactPrompt achieves 1.44$\times$ (44\% savings), while TSCG achieves up to 3.8$\times$ (74\% savings) on tool descriptions. CompactPrompt also lacks tokenizer awareness and causal attention grounding.

\textbf{ProCut} \cite{procut2025} introduces segment-level prompt compression using attribution scoring (Shapley values or leave-one-out), achieving up to 78\% reduction in production prompts. Unlike token-level methods (LLMLingua) or word-level methods (CompactPrompt), ProCut operates on semantic \emph{segments}, making it architecturally similar to TSCG's structured approach. However, ProCut requires LLM inference for attribution scoring (making it non-deterministic and API-dependent), whereas TSCG's compression is fully deterministic and zero-dependency. ProCut is an analysis tool that identifies important segments; TSCG is a compiler that transforms segments.

\subsection{Search-Based Methods}

Search-based approaches treat prompt optimization as a combinatorial search problem, exploring a space of candidate prompts to find those that maximize task performance.

\textbf{DSPy} \cite{khattab2023dspy} provides a programming framework for composing LLM calls into pipelines, with an optimizer that searches over prompt configurations using bootstrapped demonstrations and instruction tuning. DSPy's strength lies in its composability and systematic approach to prompt programming. However, its optimization is inherently non-deterministic, dependent on the specific demonstrations sampled, and does not incorporate tokenizer or attention awareness.

\textbf{OPRO} \cite{yang2024large} uses LLMs themselves as optimizers, iteratively generating and evaluating candidate prompts in a meta-optimization loop. While creative in its use of LLMs for self-improvement, OPRO produces highly variable results across runs and requires extensive API calls for the optimization process itself.

\textbf{APE} (Automatic Prompt Engineer) \cite{zhou2023large} generates candidate instructions using an LLM, then selects the best-performing instruction through evaluation on a held-out set. APE automates the prompt engineering process but provides no theoretical guarantees about the optimality of its outputs and exhibits significant run-to-run variance.

\textbf{EvoPrompt} \cite{chen2024evoprompt} applies evolutionary algorithms---specifically genetic algorithms and differential evolution---to prompt optimization, treating prompts as individuals in a population that undergo mutation and crossover. The evolutionary approach explores a broader search space than greedy methods but inherits the non-determinism of stochastic optimization.

\textbf{SAMMO} \cite{schlegel2024sammo} represents the closest search-based system to TSCG, explicitly framing itself as a ``compile-time prompt optimizer.'' SAMMO treats prompts as symbolic programs with tree structure, applying mutation operators (paraphrasing, restructuring, compression) through LLM-based beam search to find optimal prompt variants. While SAMMO shares TSCG's ``compile-time'' framing, the two systems differ fundamentally in mechanism: SAMMO is \emph{search-based} (requiring an LLM meta-optimizer for mutations, non-deterministic, runtime measured in minutes), while TSCG is \emph{rule-based} (deterministic transforms, zero LLM dependency, sub-millisecond execution). SAMMO optimizes prompt \emph{content} through stochastic search; TSCG optimizes prompt \emph{structure} through formal grammar transforms. The two could potentially compose---TSCG for structural optimization, SAMMO for content refinement---but this remains untested.

\textbf{PromptBreeder} \cite{fernando2024promptbreeder} extends the evolutionary paradigm by co-evolving both task prompts and the mutation operators themselves, enabling adaptation of the search strategy over time. While sophisticated, this approach is computationally expensive and non-reproducible.

\textbf{COSP} (Consistency-based Self-adaptive Prompting) \cite{wan2024cosp} leverages output consistency across multiple samples to self-select effective demonstrations without labeled data. This reduces the need for human annotation but introduces dependence on sampling variance.

The fundamental limitation of search-based methods is their stochastic nature: the same input can produce different optimized prompts across runs, precluding the reproducibility required for production deployment.

\subsection{Gradient-Based Methods}

Gradient-based approaches leverage access to model gradients or differentiable approximations to guide prompt optimization through gradient descent.

\textbf{TextGrad} \cite{yuksekgonul2024textgrad} introduces ``textual gradients''---natural language feedback from LLMs that serves as an analogue to numerical gradients for optimizing text-based variables. TextGrad enables backpropagation-like optimization through complex LLM pipelines but requires multiple model calls per optimization step and produces non-deterministic results.

\textbf{ProTeGi} \cite{pryzant2023automatically} generates gradient-inspired textual edits to prompts, using model feedback to identify which components of a prompt should be modified and how. Like TextGrad, ProTeGi simulates gradient-based optimization through natural language but lacks determinism and theoretical grounding in attention mechanics.

\textbf{PromptAgent} \cite{wang2023promptagent} frames prompt optimization as a planning problem, using Monte Carlo Tree Search (MCTS) to explore a space of prompt modifications guided by model feedback. While the planning framework is principled, PromptAgent requires extensive model interaction and does not guarantee reproducibility.

Gradient-based methods share the requirement for iterative model interaction during optimization, making them unsuitable for scenarios where optimization must occur client-side or without API access during the optimization phase.

\subsection{Template-Based Methods}

Template-based approaches impose structured formats on prompts, providing syntactic organization without deep theoretical grounding.

\textbf{LangGPT} \cite{wang2024langgpt} defines a dual-layer prompt structure with modules for role definition, constraints, and output format. The structured approach improves prompt organization and readability but lacks formal optimization---template compliance does not guarantee token efficiency or attention-optimal positioning.

\textbf{SSR++} \cite{wen2024ssr} introduces structured semantic reasoning templates that decompose complex tasks into organized reasoning steps. While this improves reasoning performance, SSR++ operates at the semantic level without considering tokenization or positional attention effects.

Template methods provide useful organizational structure but do not optimize at the level of tokens and attention patterns where the transformer actually operates.

\subsection{Theoretically-Grounded Methods}

\textbf{CFPO} (Causal-Flow Prompt Optimization) \cite{guo2024cfpo} represents the closest prior work to TSCG, explicitly modeling causal information flow in prompts. CFPO analyzes how information propagates through causal attention layers and optimizes prompt structure accordingly. However, CFPO does not incorporate tokenizer alignment, lacks a budgeted anchoring mechanism, and does not provide a deterministic implementation with zero dependencies.

\subsection{Positioning TSCG}

As shown in Table~\ref{tab:prior-art}, TSCG is unique in satisfying all eight desiderata simultaneously. No existing system combines tokenizer awareness with causal attention grounding, deterministic transforms, black-box compatibility, and budget-constrained anchoring. The closest systems---CFPO for theoretical grounding, LLMLingua-2 for compression, and DSPy for practical optimization---each satisfy at most four of the eight criteria. SAMMO (Microsoft, EMNLP 2024) represents the closest search-based alternative, sharing TSCG's ``compile-time'' framing but differing fundamentally in mechanism: SAMMO requires an LLM for search-based optimization, while TSCG operates as a deterministic, zero-dependency compiler. CompactPrompt is the only other LLM-free heuristic approach, but achieves only 1.44$\times$ compression compared to TSCG's 10.6$\times$ on structured content due to its restriction to lexical-level operations.

\textbf{Scope caveat.} TSCG's strength is concentrated on \emph{structured} prompt content (tool schemas, API definitions, function signatures). On natural prose, LLMLingua-2 achieves up to 20$\times$ compression versus TSCG's 1.07$\times$; on prompt content optimization, DSPy and SAMMO achieve +25--65\% accuracy improvements by optimizing \emph{what} to say, an axis TSCG does not address. TSCG is the strongest technique for a specific, underserved problem---not a general-purpose replacement for any of the above systems.

